United States: Repetition is a mother of wisdom
He even becomes a comic, the diligent effort with which Barack Obama, president with a reputation as a sage, reproduces his predecessor's strategy on the Afghan question, which he considered himself very simple.
When he ended up allowing his long-awaited doctrine to sweat, it turned out that he had copied it to carbon paper since Bush’s Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content with using in the text even several times the expression "like in Iraq", he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of the speech of Bush of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a civil war-consumed Iraq as “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its aftermath.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to be so successful that the newspapers at the moment do not speak at all about Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, that said, objectively speaking, he left his successor with a much more favourable final situation than one could hope for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
Campaign commanders again called for an increase in the military contingent, including the Afghan operation commander, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the White House's reluctance despite habits of subordination.
He asked for 40 000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he at least defrauded the general of 10 000 soldiers.
He managed to extirpate the promise of an additional 5 000 from Europe, even if he originally counted on 10 000.
What brings the most trouble into Obama’s strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and complete this entire process within three years. All of Obama’s doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that an increase in half will bring the same fruits as the progression in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out by the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
In these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders on a day-to-day basis, depending on what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only powder in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is singularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity on the reports, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "state that is quick to act", which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy puzzles by his voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the verge of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and reality-free heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent in the tumult of the war in view of their "prompt return home" will bring a real miracle.
From a political point of view, defining a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it the indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the will of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving towards the negative.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the reinforced sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult question of a resolution of the problem through the use of military force.
This will be answered, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only rustine for Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
