Czech discovery: a substance that works on "enduring" HIV viruses too
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the proliferation of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality takes, in some cases, the upper hand over the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on the common variants of the virus as well as some drugs already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at this time.
However, the lives of patients can be radically extended through a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption leads to a series of side effects.
Moreover, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of the development of so-called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have any effect.
The work of the experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the Prague VŠCHT and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a way to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarborans act on the protein responsible for multiplying the HIV virus.
Metalocarbonanes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers’ work leads them to discover new “improved” substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bindings on the virus’ proteins.
Metalocarbonans have a single three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metallic atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If the HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus will also be stopped in the patient's body, the researchers said in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
