Vaccination against pneumococcal disease will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococci will reverse old habits in January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Voices are already rising, saying that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free vaccination against pneumococcal disease culminate.
The pharmaceutical institute already defines for vaccines the maximum prices that health insurance will pay.
Specialists also see clear in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for August kids.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococcal disease.
The condition is that they have not been vaccinated yet.
If we started vaccination last year or earlier, we will have to pay for the following vaccinations.
The first dose of vaccine should be administered between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Last year, a quarter of the families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcal disease.
However, parents paid 1600 crowns or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Specialists estimate that every year health insurance spends 300 to 450 000 kronor in vaccine doses.
However, they save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
Until now, the State has spent about 500 000 kronor per year on all vaccination of children.
The reimbursed vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococci are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the meninges and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, there are up to 28 deaths of children under 10 years of age caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries introduced reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions on a possible vaccination obligation in the future.
From January, it must be regulated by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that mandatory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted vaccination against pneumococci.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we were able to impose at least this.
I think this is a direction that must now be followed, said Kalovský.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the process of vaccination against pneumococci.
We are absolutely not considering it at the moment, said its spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, say doctors.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Society for Pediatricians, acknowledges that a voluntary vaccination will be defected.
If all children were vaccinated, we could consider a decrease in the renewals of vaccinations "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional" says however Cabrnochová.
Specialists predict that as early as next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
Vaccination against pneumococci also marks a rupture of the fact that it is the first vaccination of children that is financed by insurance and not the state.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance should release funds for prevention, saving on possible future medical care.
