Drafted in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is, without a doubt, the most controversial obligation introduced by the communist government.
Couples who violate this policy may have to pay colossal fines - up to three times their annual income - and suffer discrimination in the workplace.
Chinese authorities have given the police the duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the execution of this policy.
In rural areas, some representatives of the authority have forced pregnant women of a second child to have an abortion.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to a ratio of boys – abnormally high girls.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for city residents, members of ethnic minorities, and cases in which men and women are already single children -- and in 2007 they softened many of their harsh slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at Peking University, said central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child have been replaced by copies of retailing regulations that have the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city government has dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet with couples, at their home, and slip leaflets under their doorstep.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the head of family planning, the response was disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural town in the suburbs of Shanghai say they saw an increase in requests for records of couples wishing for a second child after the campaign was launched, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115 000 inhabitants, for example, still receives only four to five requests per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still projected to be only about 165 000 -- slightly higher than 2009 but less than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee in Shanghai’s Caolu commune, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don’t want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally allowed to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and life insurance given by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners mistakenly consider the one-child policy to be a rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple’s first child.
It's true, we're being robbed of luck having more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, the Human Resources Manager, said she only wanted an only child because she was one herself. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us."
We are not used to taking care of someone else and we really do not want to take care of others.”
Chen Zijian, 42, who owns a translation company, says so more crudely.
For couples working together, middle-class, who lower the birth rate, he says, you have to be selfish to succeed.
People aged 20 or 30 grew up seeing their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and don’t want to have that lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even a single child takes a lot of time from his parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the space problems -- "You have to change your apartment" -- and planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you have to write his resume to get a place in the best kindergarten."
