We don’t want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations Group has draft plans for emission reduction
The UN-sponsored climate conference — characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations — came back in the spotlight on Friday, due to the release of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations weighing most of the burden in the coming times.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it has illuminated the way to go.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in negotiations that is short of time, with more than 100 leaders from around the world coming next week to Copenhagen.
Drafted by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both over the course and in the long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and emerging new economies could decrease their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature rise that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative at Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN’s Executive Secretary-General on climate change, Yvo de Boer, described as “the full picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions in 2020, from 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce theirs by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion per year for the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to cope with floods and drought or to prevent deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, U.S. Representative for Climate Negotiations, rejected any discussion that required the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts made by the major emerging economies, if they were not financed by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is becoming tougher on China than the Bush administration was tough two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions by the major developing countries, says Stern who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the U.S. lead negotiator either lacked “common sense” or was “extremely irresponsible” for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not help China financially to combat global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the world’s major powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about rescuing individual economies than the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States quarreling over their respective obligations as poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives of acting more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers are fighting over who should be subject to the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in their attempt to make major emitters responsible for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, which is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to put pressure on a legally obliging treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say the negotiations will lead to a minimum, a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of Climate Unity of the European Commission, said that the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the full political process", in part by what they are now unified and that they ask emerging economies such as China and India, to act.
The debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the pending issues before heads of government reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Minister of Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister got off their plane and rushed to the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and information conferences, so they could make claims that will be considered in the following week.
The real image of the rally -- in which 13 000 people enter and leave the Convention Centre every day -- guitar activists present nighttime shows that they believe are becoming betrayed and proposals are being written and distributed on paper rather than by emails -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the greats, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy of Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
