The 62-year-old photographer, known for his photos of stars, will be tried on April 15 and 16, 2010 for abuse of weakness, a crime punishable by a maximum sentence of three years imprisonment and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will be a trial in this case worthy of a saga on one of the wealthiest families in France, in which mother and daughter tear each other apart while holding the reins of the empire of L'Oréal cosmetics.
But the 15th Correctional Chamber also ordered that a medical expertise of 87-year-old Liliane Bettencourt should be conducted collectively by three doctors.
The heiress and main shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such an examination, at least not under the conditions proposed by the prosecutor's office of Nanterre during the investigation.
The doctors designated Friday will have to submit a report before March 10, 2010, in particular, whether Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness and at what periods.
I think she'll submit to it.
I'll talk to him about it," said Ms. Bettencourt's lawyer, Me Georges Kiejman, at the outset of the hearing.
For his part, the lawyer of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the decision of the court.
This is great news (...) The expertise will show that he (M. Banier) manipulated this elderly lady who must be protected, he said.
For the past two years, the only daughter of Liliane Bettencourt has been in criminal proceedings against François-Marie Banier, photographer and artist touch-to-all, whom she accuses of having taken advantage for years of the weakness of her mother to obtain a billion euros of donations, in the form of checks, life insurance contracts or master paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always refuted to have been manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a long-time friend.
While the court had to examine the admissibility of the action taken by Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers, the pleas of the lawyers sometimes turned to great family unpacking Friday.
Thus, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer reported three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was suspicious of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the letter dated 2003, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
Françoise, I have never been able to talk to him since her marriage."
For her part, the Nanterre prosecutor's office again considered that the complainant was not admissible to act, especially since a guardianship judge has refused in recent days to grant her request to open a judicial protection procedure for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to take legal action, she is not under protection and does not have a guardian.
No one else has to act in his place," said Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney, a representative of the public prosecutor.
The court finally ruled that it would rule once the trial took place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Managerial revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the big French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it was once, to impose on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets back to the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors returns regularly!
A demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, even more, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "demands a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision from all stakeholders"; it requires on the part of employees a commitment that authoritarian management revenues totally upset.
This is why we call for a managerial revolution that would involve putting employees at the center of the company’s concerns in the same way as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid I'm not.
- First of all because I could see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally happens, after many detours, to do priority... what it has always done. !
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the great engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the American "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of the commitment of executives, a recent survey of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for the world of today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, the commitment for the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a way to realize a part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from reason-to-oncentional analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "at the place".
They thus create a favorable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo's speech: "just war" is worth praise to the right in Obama
The U.S. right on Friday welcomed the speech delivered the day before in Oslo by Barack Obama, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of a "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who had brocaded the award of the prize to Mr. Obama on October 9 applauded the presidential speech, like Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, said Ms. Palin, a regimer of the right wing of the Republican Party, to the USA Today daily, adding that she herself addressed the theme of the war "sometimes necessary" in her memoirs that have just been published.
The war is of course the last thing I think the Americans want to have to do, but it is necessary.
We have to stop these terrorists all over there, she said.
M. Obama, who inherited the two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of M. Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, said the former president of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential statement.
On some sides, I found this speech quite historical, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected official, considered by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not present a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
Michael Gerson, former pen by George W. Bush converted columnist at the Washington Post, M. Obama gave “a very American speech.”
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke like an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a bubble of security that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it," said Mr. Gerson.
Among the few on the right who is not convinced, a Bush-era hawk, former UN ambassador John Bolton, called the speech “dull, light-headed and uninspired” on the National Review Online website.
To the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed that Barack Obama was justifying the use of force.
When we wrap war in the notion of justice, we can easily justify the massacre of innocent people, he warned.
The center-left press, however, remained rave about the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel was awarded prematurely to Mr. Obama called his speech a “superproduction” even for a speaker known for his talent.
Oslo's speech "should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression," the California daily newspaper said.
M. Obama “gave the right speech,” the New York Times said, deeming it “both dark and uplifting.”
Roads: three marathons for a deal that saves Christmas supplies
After three sessions of marathon negotiations, the unions of the road sector and TLF, the only employers' organization to have remained until the end, reached Friday night an agreement that puts an end to the slogan of strike and the threat to the supplies of Christmas.
During the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, "rejoiced" in this agreement, after several sessions of negotiations, begun Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions the negotiators had left in the early morning Friday, with the hope of signing quickly at the end of the morning the text of agreement.
And this even if three employers' organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it took even more than six hours of a meeting started at 11am for everyone to agree and that at 6pm the text was signed.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to companies" and "it was to be feared that it would come to disrupt the holiday season," said Mr. Bussereau.
The text provides for a 4% increase in wages for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and by 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
In hourly rates, for low-wages, "we go from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It's not much, but we start from a very far distance, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
We will order our activists to have no blockages, no blockades of the supply centres.
But we can still have some recalcitrants that are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, welcomed "a good agreement", even if it was "difficult to concede the increases on high wages given the international competition".
According to him, the increases will be of the order of 170 euros monthly for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
This is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) said "an acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for the revaluation of travel expenses by 3%, and the maintenance of the general conditions of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will make it possible in particular to address the question of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
M. Bussereau recalled that "a reduction of 100 million euros in employer's expenses" was the subject of a government amendment to the amending finance bill for 2009, voted in the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "in the same term."
The signing of TLF allows the agreement to apply initially to companies that are members of this organization, and secondly to the entire profession, in the event of an extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be done "as soon as possible", assured Mr. Bussereau.
Opposition from employers' organizations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "dupe market", because the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate urgently, not at the conclusion of a shared analysis, but not to upset the turkey eaters of the next New Year's Eve, lamented the Unostra.
For the Otre, the agreement is likely "to dig into the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
RER A: disruptions this weekend, unions unhappy with RATP proposals
The disruptions on the RER A, the largest urban transit line in France, will continue during the weekend, while a meeting Friday on the 2nd day of strike between unions and RATP management left them hungry about their request for a bonus.
Saturday and Sunday, for this important weekend of purchases before Christmas, there will be trains only between 10am and 8pm, at the rate of one train out of two on the central section (between La Défense and Nation) and one train out of four outside the central section.
Interconnection with the SNCF will be suspended at Nanterre Préfecture, which will require passengers to change trains.
Galeries Lafayette, which expect 200,000 customers every day, were delighted that "RATP is making efforts to serve department stores".
The RER A crosses from west to east the Parisian agglomeration.
The RATP section runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
On Friday, about one in two trains ran at rush hour, and almost no train in off-peak hours, as planned.
Like Thursday, there was no rush on the docks, the Ile-de-France people having organized.
Thus, in the early morning, the resort of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) was much less frequented than usual, especially because of the absence of middle and high school students.
In Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne), Jack Nbakina, a 29-year-old engineer, explained that he had stood up "an hour and a half earlier, to be sure to arrive on time".
The Saint-Lazare train station has not experienced saturation, said the SNCF, which had planned a framework of agents and police.
The RER A operated by the SNCF from or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or left the Saint-Lazare station to reach the metros.
New general assemblies of strikers will be held Saturday and Sunday, which will examine the results, considered "slim" by the unions, of a meeting with the management Friday afternoon.
The Director of RERs proposes to negotiate a specific protocol for the RER A on all aspects, working time, career progress etc.
This is not what drivers want, who claim a bonus due, according to Thierry Garon (South).
The RATP even puts its premium proposals in brackets, the CGT was outraged, stressing that the management "was not screwed to solve a problem while among the truckers and the SNCF it is done".
A new meeting is scheduled for "a broader review of the conditions of practice of the profession", the RATP said.
This also made the unions say that the company "mocked the users of the weekend".
In the morning, some 150 drivers had invaded a committee of establishment at the headquarters in Paris.
It was then that the management, which until then refused any discussion during the strike, had suggested "in the interest of appeasement" the meeting.
The conflict threatens to expand to the RER B on Tuesday, after Unsa and Independents filed a notice.
The unions ask for a premium of 120 euros (Unsa) to 150 euros including 30 euros variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, South, Independents) and complain about the deterioration of working conditions on this line to the million daily travelers.
RER drivers, all in the second part of their careers, receive from 2,200 to 2,700 euros gross as well as 600 to 650 euros of premiums, for shifted schedules, Sundays and public holidays.
Turkish justice dissolves pro-Kurdish party, decision far-reaching
Turkey’s Constitutional Court on Friday ruled the dissolution of the country’s main pro-Kurdish party, a move that was immediately followed by angry protests in the Kurdish community, the southeast of the country and Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "home of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Court President Hasim Kiliç told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, said Mr. Kiliç, adding that 37 of the party’s executives, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the waiver of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Mrs Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's property.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sitting as parliamentarians without a label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party says, however, that it has "no organic ties" to the PKK but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights, to try to dry up the Kurds’ support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders had said a dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous protests against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
As soon as the justice was announced, a thousand protesters gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the large city of the southeast populated mostly by Kurds.
Police fired tear gas and used water cannons, as protesters threw molotov cocktails or stones, with slingshots.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk said the Justice decision would "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue by banning a party, he told reporters.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed to the closure of the parties in principle.
This does not solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a total torpedo of the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow can fall
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a very harsh winter.
But the head of the clearing and sandblasting service (FES) specifies that it is not to annoy the citizens.
This is simply so that agents can test the vehicle technique and learn how to master them well.
And according to the meterologists, it could be for this weekend.
More than 300 agents and 120 vehicles stand ready to tackle snow and ice.
The ESF follows a very elaborate plan.
M. Brauburger explains that as soon as it snows on the city of Frankfurt and that temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles travel through 20 main routes (called routes A).
This includes high traffic streets, main arteries, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire access, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as the Atzelbergstraße.
FES agents start their service at three in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometers of road must be salted with a road fondant that adheres well, in 3 hours maximum time.
This is why the FES service begins at 3am "so that the roads are cleared when the traffic of daily migration begins".
There or it gets harder, it's when the snow starts to fall at 7h30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the clearing and sandblasting service of the roads "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it no longer snows, we take care of the access roads and the service routes - like the Rat-Beil-Straße.
The secondary roads and the side streets come last.
M. Brauburger knows that this still causes some complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the FES footing team is in the way to identify priority the areas considered dangerous and the passages.
As for bike paths, the services of the ESF generally cannot take care of them.
M. Brauburger specifies that there is a special service in Frankfurt which monitors the condition of the bridges between 22hours and 4h30.
Since the ice forms very quickly on these surfaces, the salting vehicles occur as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
Sometimes the police also use this special service in case of need.
The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled the other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long for 1.50m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would not have had anything exceptional.
But, as reported by Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa Hallae is one of the earliest dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico which was at the time part of the land of the supercontinent, the Pangea and was towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa illuminates the evolution of the first dinosaurs with a new day.
Indeed, it informs us about the relationships, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in one day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Triassic.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories concerning the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named him Tawa after the Hopi Indians for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a quite exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery particularly spectacular, but it does not allow it to confirm certain theories concerning the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Among other things, experts wonder when the saurians have divided into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) that include the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor that appeared later and descended by birds, sauropods, quadrupeds with long necks, and those related to them and ornithischian herbivores of which are part the species such as the
Based on studies from S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting report of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae possessed small aerial sacs in its bones at the level of the skull, as did the birds that are the descendants of theropods.
These small pockets of air facilitate the breathing of birds compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small aerial sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the immense sauropods also possessed aerial sacs and a light bone, it may be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most early known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
Therefore, the three great lines of evolution have divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. all the land that formed the supercontinent Pangea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that would have migrated, the researchers argue.
Alan Turner of the Museum of Natural History in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, the silesaur, which lived in present-day Poland and which belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him this could give a misguided vision because there are in South America a large number of dinosaur fossils that have been preserved while almost none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how did the dinosaurs manage to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, still remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as with the ancestors of the current crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread throughout the planet thus favoring the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such a success is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction that dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better adapted and they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favorite meteorite blooming of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that since that time had been vegetating in the shadows: they were mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley in California.
There are those lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
The evacuation by the police of the casino of J.W. University. Goethe of Frankfurt is making waves all over the planet.
278 professors and teachers of J.W. University Goethe but also other higher education institutions in Germany, Europe and North and South America express their solidarity with the protesting students of the Westend Campus.
In a statement written in German and English they condemn the intervention of the police requested by the university's steering committee.
Last week, the President of the University Werner Müller-Estler had evacuated the buildings occupied by the striking students and teachers after walls and works of art were smeared with graffiti.
Five students were injured in the evacuation.
The signatories consider that the degradations did not justify "such violent intervention by the police commando against students and teachers who had organized their own courses".
The evacuation represents an "unacceptable attack" on freedom of research and teaching.
Focusing attention exclusively on acts of vandalism only serves to "delegitimize and criminalize protest" and tries to make forget the reasons for the mobilization.
The University's Steering Committee thus evaded the debates that would be essential.
The lecturers demand that the criminal proceedings instituted be immediately suspended.
The majority of the occupants did not take part in the degradations.
Legitimization of protests
The young people of the Verdi trade union in the service sector and the German Confederation of Trade Unions (DGB) show solidarity with students.
Protests are only the legitimate expression of growing concern for our own future, says Alexander Klein, regional youth secretary for the Verdi union.
As for the Minister of Science of the Land of Hesse Eva Kühne-Hörmann (CDU) , she took the case for the action taken by the President of the University and the police.
We thank the President of the University.
Any occupation and degradation of the premises is totally unacceptable, she told the regional parliament in Wiesbaden last Thursday during the television show Aktuelle Stunde.
We understand the meaning of the protests but do not accept vandalism, expressed CDU member of the Regional Parliament Peter Beuth.
The parliamentary groups of the SPD opposition, the Greens and the Left (die Linke) did not share this opinion.
The CSU takes the pretext of a few painted walls to criminalize the protests, said Janine Wissler of the party La Gauche (Linke)
Instead of thinking about the arguments and demands of the students, we evacuate them.
The Left Party has tabled a motion that summons the Minister of the Interior to submit a report on the conditions of the intervention of the police.
The new Silicon Valley
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place for the search for secret weapons, under strict surveillance.
Today with its 216 000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the Soviet “Silicon Valley”.
Important production and research locations in micro- and nanoelectronics are located.
In September 2008 representatives of Zelenograd have created links with Riedberg, a place of Frankfurt science – with the academic institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a “Protocol of Close Cooperation”.
The signatories were the Vice Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz project section chief for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will leave for a seminar in Zelenograd.
Scientific Exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will allow FIZ companies to enter the growing Russian market.
Russian scientific companies want to obtain contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the headquarters of famous Soviet institutes and research societies.
There is the Moscow Institute of Electrical Engineering, the major firms Sitronics and Rosssizhskaja-Elektronika.
The town was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for armament research.
Zelenograd (literal translation “Green City”) takes its name from the wooded hills in the heart of which the research centers are located.
Project S21: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be placed high enough.
For his supporters, this is nothing less than “new heart of Europe”.
If we will. S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg, into a desperate chaos of construction sites for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 80s.
The head-on stations, with tracks that ended in the city, had a reputation at the time for being the relics of the 19th-century transport technique that had the effect of a brake hoof of modern rail traffic because it once took a long time to move the locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that’s what you have to do.
That’s why the head-on stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart too: a train station, which is about halfway on the Trans-European Rail Magistral between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realization of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 80's have not been compatible with reality for a long time.
Even the most ambitious planners recognized that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, head-on-line stations no longer really pose entry and exit problems since there are modern, reversible trains with railcars and pilot cars at both ends.
However, the realization of Stuttgart 21 is now launched next to the new route of the inter-city line towards Ulm.
Regional and communal policies have prevailed.
The railway company is in the game because, it is the taxpayer who pays the risks of the largest infrastructure project of the federal republic and not the public enterprise.
From an urbanistic point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
We get an urban space that – according to the graphs of computer-generated planners – will be very green.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
