It is our imagination that is at issue: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but sometimes encourages the limits between dreaming, madness and reality to blend.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can be presented in the most diverse forms, in the best case, this is called visions, at worst of madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect stand out, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of the shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There is hallucinations or delusions when balance, neurotransmitting substances in the brain – primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and achetylcholine – breaks and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts often manifest during schizophrenic psychosis.
The earthly force of attraction has no more power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and dreaming.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of awakened dream; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, found in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
