What is crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten de Lübeck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy very expensive drugs to get them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been gathering reports for ten years on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The Unreal World in Our Heads".
Hunculinations are indeed part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also of an impressive number of many other pathologies.
They include psychological disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer’s disease or head trauma.
It is surprising to find that under certain conditions even the brains of healthy people are subject to hallucinations.
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions, are overactive or not sufficiently reburned; when our brain heats up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like a brain injury or psychosis.
But also lack of stimulus, stress, heartbreaks or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one-third of participants admit to having experienced a hallucination at least once in their life.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Previous Pomerania and goes to high school.
A normal girl to actually say.
If there were no images and voices.
During recess, it happens that a young boy, thin, with long chestnut hair, speaks to him.
When she answers her comrades, she looks at her, amazed – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a lunatic dreamer but Sarah K doesn’t dream, she’s sure.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
She can even perceive her presence momentarily.
It’s a pleasant feeling, she finds this young friendly.
Am I crazy?, she wonders sometimes.
But she knows that this young person and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
Often the visions are heavy.
When she is in class, it happens that she cannot take the course because the teacher is just presenting a new student in his eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is visibly explaining equations on the board.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she waits for sleep that arrives too rarely and far too late, she often cannot make the distinction if she is awake or dreams already, if the images she sees, the grimacing faces or the girl with bloody notches on her arms and legs are in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she shouts to these creatures.
She doesn’t talk to her parents or her friends, they would take her for a crazy woman.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She graduated last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she came into contact via the internet with psychologist Kasten she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the probability is high that they will have hallucinations after a while.
I guess the brain isn’t busy enough, so there’s animation.
Sarah K., the only girl, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13, that the man she called Dad, since she was old enough to think, was not her real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, so it’s very difficult for people like Sarah K to tell the difference between illusion and reality. "Every experience," according to Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is formed from there.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
For Kasten, nightlife is also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychoses.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
This is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a special talent.
There is only one step between dream and hallucination.
In our world too centered on consciousness, we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief medical officer of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease but also contains something positive, creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid form of experience, a particular form of the modification of the awakened consciousness by the dream.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that it cannot differentiate from the dream even when it is in a state of awakening.
The state of oniroid consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with polyradiculopathy who fully aware, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that harms his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world is taking place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is in fact an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation, a capacity for organization given to us, to us men, so as not to sink into the nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real later in memories.
The Zurich-based Peter Cornelius Classen, an art historian, also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Change of the Heart" as an action to safeguard the soul.
He is 49 years old, at a time when his conscious leaves on a trip of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; meanwhile, his body is condemned to remain still in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created from scratch, visit foreign places, travel back in time. He sees himself as an old man who is a bed in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who make blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek motorcycle who takes him to his country, surfs with his hospital bed in the vene of the Alps and meets a Korean mafia.
He is completely absorbed in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes, describing what he has been through.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oniroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a state of watch.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
