75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their maternity
Discrimination in the workplace has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study “Fecundity and professional career of women in Spain”, carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of life in a couple and the number of children, whether or not the woman is working and the type of job being held.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time or have unstable work, get into a relationship earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
In contrast, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back into life as a couple and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in a relationship. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. “These data show that women with stable jobs needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to push back the union and arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences motherhood, but less the date of the beginning of a common life,” explains the researcher of the CSIC Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap in the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also among the women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between the ages of 35 and 49, those who completed elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
“Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those with medium- or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child,” says Delgado.
