Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As has taken place with the ABS anti-lock system and as will take place with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen pedestrian protection, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by car component manufacturer Bosch, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident were unable to pull the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken full advantage of their strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1 100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be prevented each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is calculated that one in four claims with injured would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps him by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts the maximum effort on the brakes to minimize the damage.
